digit ``1'' appears in roughly 30% of the cases, the digit ``2'' in 18% of the cases, and the digit {{2305.05403_FO0080||FO}} in {{2305.05403_FO0081||FO}} percent of the cases. This applies in particular to quantities that grow exponentially (such as the population of a city), because a quantity to which a multiplicative factor is applied repeatedly will run through the leading digit ``1'' more often than through the other digits. To apply this technique to KBs [soulet2018representativeness], the target class has to have a numerical predicate, e.g., the population size for cities, the length for rivers, the price for products, etc.